<h1 id="overview">DocGen User Guide</h1>
<p>Everything you need to create templates, generate documents, and automate document workflows in Salesforce.</p>

<!-- ==================== GETTING STARTED ==================== -->

<div class="card">
    <h3>What is DocGen?</h3>
    <p>DocGen generates PDFs, Word docs, Excel spreadsheets, and PowerPoint decks by merging live Salesforce data into your templates. 100% native, zero external dependencies, runs entirely on the Salesforce platform.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="installation">Installation &amp; Setup</h2>

<ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Install the package</strong> using the link from the <a href="/DocGenLanding">landing page</a> or GitHub. Choose "Install for Admins Only" to start.</li>
    <li><strong>Assign permission sets.</strong> Go to Setup &gt; Permission Sets and assign <strong>DocGen Admin</strong> (full access) or <strong>DocGen User</strong> (generate only) to your users.</li>
    <li><strong>Enable Blob.toPdf() Release Update.</strong> Go to Setup &gt; Release Updates and enable <em>"Use the Visualforce PDF Rendering Service for Blob.toPdf() Invocations"</em>. Without this, PDFs will show raw text instead of formatted content.</li>
    <li><strong>Add the component to record pages.</strong> Edit any Lightning Record Page, drag the <code>docGenRunner</code> component onto the layout, save and activate. Repeat for each object where users need to generate documents.</li>
    <li><strong>Open the DocGen app.</strong> Use the App Launcher to find "DocGen" — this is the Command Hub where admins create and manage templates.</li>
</ol>

<div class="warning">
    <strong>Required:</strong> The Blob.toPdf() Release Update must be enabled for PDF generation. Without it, PDFs render incorrectly. This is opt-in until Summer '26 when Salesforce enforces it for all orgs.
</div>

<h2 id="quick-start">Quick Start</h2>

<ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Create a template.</strong> In the DocGen app, click Create New. Name it, choose your object (Account, Opportunity, etc.), and select a sample record for preview.</li>
    <li><strong>Build your query.</strong> Type your SOQL in the editor — autocomplete suggests fields as you type. Add merge tags to your Word file: <code>{Name}</code> for a field, <code>{Account.Name}</code> for a parent, <code>{#Contacts}{FirstName}{/Contacts}</code> for child records.</li>
    <li><strong>Upload your template file.</strong> Upload a <code>.docx</code>, <code>.xlsx</code>, or <code>.pptx</code> file containing your merge tags. Use the Copy-Paste Tags panel to see all available tags.</li>
    <li><strong>Generate.</strong> Go to any record page with the DocGen component, select your template, and click Generate. Done.</li>
</ol>

<!-- ==================== TEMPLATES ==================== -->

<h2 id="creating-templates">Creating Templates</h2>

<p>Templates are created in the <strong>DocGen Command Hub</strong> (the DocGen app tab). The wizard walks you through three steps:</p>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Step 1 — Name &amp; Configure</h3>
    <p>Give your template a name, select the type (Word, Excel, or PowerPoint), choose the output format (PDF or Native), and pick the base Salesforce object. Optionally select a sample record — this powers the live data preview on step 2. You can also add a category and description for organization.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Step 2 — Build Your Query</h3>
    <p>Type your SOQL query directly in the editor. As you type, inline autocomplete suggests fields from the object schema. Type <code>Owner.</code> to see User fields, type <code>(</code> to see child relationships. You can also paste a full SOQL statement — DocGen automatically strips the <code>SELECT ... FROM</code> wrapper and keeps just the field list.</p>
    <p>If you selected a sample record on step 1, a live preview tree appears showing real values from your query: field names with actual data, child records in mini-tables. This lets you verify your query returns the right data before uploading a template.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Step 3 — Upload Your File</h3>
    <p>Upload a <code>.docx</code>, <code>.xlsx</code>, or <code>.pptx</code> file containing merge tags. The <strong>Copy-Paste Tags</strong> panel shows all available tags from your query — including nested child and grandchild fields at every level. Click any tag to copy it, then paste into your template file.</p>
</div>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Tip:</strong> Set a <strong>Document Title Format</strong> in the template settings to auto-name generated files. Use merge tags like <code>Invoice_{Name}_{CloseDate}</code>. The generated file will be named using real data from the record.
</div>

<h2 id="query-builder">Query Builder</h2>

<p>The query builder is a manual-first SOQL editor with smart suggestions. Type your query directly — no drag-and-drop, no multi-panel UI.</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Inline Autocomplete</strong> — Start typing a field name and suggestions appear from the object schema. Click to insert with auto-comma formatting.</li>
    <li><strong>Context-Aware</strong> — Type <code>Owner.</code> and it loads User fields. Type <code>(</code> and it shows child relationships. Inside a subquery like <code>(SELECT ... FROM Contacts)</code>, it suggests Contact fields.</li>
    <li><strong>Paste Full SOQL</strong> — Paste a complete <code>SELECT ... FROM ... WHERE</code> statement directly. DocGen auto-strips the SELECT/FROM wrapper and keeps the field list. Outer WHERE clauses trigger a warning so you know to move filters to the subquery level.</li>
    <li><strong>Nested Subqueries</strong> — Build multi-level relationships at any depth: Account &gt; Opportunities &gt; Line Items &gt; Schedules. Subqueries parse correctly and Copy-Paste Tags generate for all nesting levels.</li>
    <li><strong>Parent Lookups</strong> — Use dot notation for related fields: <code>Account.Name</code>, <code>Owner.Email</code>, <code>Account.Owner.Name</code></li>
    <li><strong>Child Subqueries</strong> — Add subqueries with optional WHERE, ORDER BY, and LIMIT: <code>(SELECT FirstName, LastName FROM Contacts WHERE Active__c = true ORDER BY LastName LIMIT 100)</code></li>
    <li><strong>Sample Record Preview</strong> — Pick a sample record on step 1, and step 2 shows real values from your query in a structured tree with child records in mini-tables.</li>
    <li><strong>Quick Reference</strong> — Syntax examples for fields, parent lookups, and subqueries displayed below the editor.</li>
    <li><strong>Trailing Comma Cleanup</strong> — Trailing commas are auto-stripped when clicking Next, so you don't have to worry about syntax.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="template-formats">Template Formats</h2>

<p>DocGen supports four template formats. Word and HTML can both produce PDFs; Excel and PowerPoint render in their native file formats.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Format</th><th>Template File</th><th>Output Options</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Word</strong></td><td><code>.docx</code></td><td>PDF or DOCX</td><td>Contracts, proposals, invoices, letters</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>HTML</strong> <em>(v1.61+)</em></td><td><code>.html</code>, <code>.htm</code>, <code>.zip</code></td><td>PDF</td><td>Google Docs, Notion, ChatGPT, Apple Pages &mdash; any HTML source</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Excel</strong></td><td><code>.xlsx</code></td><td>XLSX</td><td>Data exports, reports, financial summaries</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>PowerPoint</strong></td><td><code>.pptx</code></td><td>PPTX</td><td>Presentations, slide decks</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Word is still the most feature-complete &mdash; barcodes and QR codes are currently Word-only. HTML templates unlock a whole class of authoring tools that don't produce <code>.docx</code> (Google Docs' Web Page export is the flagship workflow). See the <a href="#html-templates">HTML Templates</a> section for the full authoring guide. Excel and PowerPoint accept every merge tag but output in their native formats only.</p>

<h2 id="html-templates">HTML Templates (Google Docs, Notion, any HTML source)</h2>

<p>HTML templates (shipped in v1.61) are a new way to author DocGen templates using any tool that can export HTML. Output is always PDF. Every merge tag that works in Word templates works identically in HTML templates &mdash; <code>&#123;Name&#125;</code>, loops, conditionals, aggregates, images, page numbers, <code>&#123;Today&#125;</code>, <code>&#123;Now&#125;</code>.</p>

<p><strong>Why HTML templates?</strong> Word templates lock you into the Microsoft Word authoring experience. HTML templates let your team design in Google Docs, Notion, ChatGPT, Apple Pages, or any rich-text editor that produces HTML. Design where your content lives, keep the DocGen merge-tag engine the same.</p>

<h3>Authoring in Google Docs (recommended)</h3>

<ol>
    <li>Design the document in Google Docs. Use normal formatting &mdash; headings, tables, images, colors, fonts.</li>
    <li>Add merge tags as plain text where you want data from Salesforce: <code>&#123;Name&#125;</code>, <code>&#123;Account.Name&#125;</code>, <code>&#123;Amount:currency&#125;</code>, loops like <code>&#123;#Contacts&#125;...&#123;/Contacts&#125;</code>. All the merge tag syntax from Word templates works identically &mdash; see Merge Tags in the sidebar for the full reference.</li>
    <li>Go to <strong>File &gt; Download &gt; Web Page (.html, zipped)</strong>. Google Docs produces a <code>.zip</code> containing your HTML plus an <code>images/</code> folder with every image in the doc.</li>
    <li>In the DocGen Command Hub, click <strong>Create Template</strong>, set <strong>Type</strong> to <strong>HTML</strong>. Output Format is automatically locked to <strong>PDF</strong>.</li>
    <li>On the Upload step, drop the <code>.zip</code> file. DocGen unzips it in your browser, extracts each image into a Salesforce ContentVersion linked to the template, and rewrites the HTML's <code>&lt;img src="images/..."&gt;</code> references to <code>/sfc/servlet.shepherd/version/download/&lt;cvId&gt;</code> URLs that <code>Blob.toPdf</code> resolves natively.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Save as New Version</strong>. The template is live.</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Why unzip in the browser?</strong> Salesforce's default File Upload Security setting blocks <code>.zip</code> uploads with "Your company doesn't support the following file types: .zip". DocGen sidesteps that by reading the zip bytes with a pure-JavaScript ZIP reader (no external dependencies), pulling out the <code>.html</code> + images, and uploading only the extracted pieces via Apex. The <code>.zip</code> itself never becomes a ContentVersion, so the org setting never sees it. Bonus: unzipping on the client keeps Apex heap flat regardless of template size.</p>

<h3>Other authoring tools</h3>

<p>Any tool that can export or paste HTML works. Upload the resulting <code>.html</code> or <code>.htm</code> file directly:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Notion / Confluence</strong> &mdash; export the page as HTML.</li>
    <li><strong>ChatGPT / Claude</strong> &mdash; ask it to generate HTML, paste into a plain text file with a <code>.html</code> extension.</li>
    <li><strong>Apple Pages</strong> &mdash; File &gt; Export To &gt; HTML.</li>
    <li><strong>Hand-written HTML</strong> &mdash; any text editor works. Merge tags are plain text.</li>
</ul>

<p>For single-file uploads, DocGen scans the HTML for inline <code>&lt;img src="data:image/..."&gt;</code> URIs (Notion and ChatGPT frequently emit these for pasted images) and converts each to a ContentVersion. <code>Blob.toPdf</code> can't decode data URIs directly, so this conversion is what makes the images actually render in the final PDF.</p>

<h3>Header &amp; Footer fields</h3>

<p>HTML templates have dedicated <strong>Header HTML</strong> and <strong>Footer HTML</strong> fields on a Header / Footer tab in the template edit modal. Each field has:</p>

<ul>
    <li>A WYSIWYG rich-text editor with bold, italic, alignment, color, images, and links.</li>
    <li>A <strong>Show HTML</strong> / <strong>Show Editor</strong> toggle that flips to a monospace textarea showing the raw HTML &mdash; useful when you need to set image widths, apply inline styles, or adjust markup the rich editor can't expose.</li>
</ul>

<p>Every merge tag that works in the body works in the header and footer: <code>&#123;Name&#125;</code>, <code>&#123;Today:date&#125;</code>, <code>&#123;Owner.Name&#125;</code>, etc. Values resolve per-record at generation time.</p>

<h3>Page Numbers</h3>

<p>Put <code>&#123;PageNumber&#125;</code> and <code>&#123;TotalPages&#125;</code> in the Header HTML or Footer HTML field. At render time these compile to Flying Saucer CSS page counters inside the PDF's page-margin boxes. Each page gets its own correctly-updated counter &mdash; "Page 3 of 17" on page 3, "Page 4 of 17" on page 4, automatically.</p>

<pre style="background:#f4f6f9;padding:0.75rem;border-radius:4px;"><code>&lt;div style="text-align:center; font-size:9pt; color:#888;"&gt;
  Page &#123;PageNumber&#125; of &#123;TotalPages&#125;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

<p><strong>Flying Saucer limitation:</strong> CSS page counters only resolve inside <code>@page</code> margin rules &mdash; not on DOM elements. When a header or footer contains <code>&#123;PageNumber&#125;</code> or <code>&#123;TotalPages&#125;</code>, DocGen renders it as plain text in the page-margin box (no inline images or rich formatting in that margin). A header <em>without</em> counter tokens stays full rich HTML. <strong>Practical workaround:</strong> logo / rich content in the header (no counters), page count in the footer (counters only). Or the reverse. Both fields can be populated simultaneously.</p>

<h3>Images in HTML Templates</h3>

<p>Three ways to get images into an HTML template:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Google Docs zip</strong> &mdash; any image inserted in the Google Doc is bundled into the <code>.zip</code> export. On upload, each is extracted into its own ContentVersion automatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Inline data URIs</strong> &mdash; HTML like <code>&lt;img src="data:image/png;base64,..."/&gt;</code> (produced by Notion, ChatGPT, and rich-text editors for pasted images) is scanned on upload and each data URI is saved as its own ContentVersion with the <code>src</code> rewritten.</li>
    <li><strong>Record-attached merge tags</strong> &mdash; <code>&#123;%Image:N&#125;</code> (Nth image attached to the current record) and <code>&#123;%FieldName&#125;</code> (field value is a ContentVersion ID) both emit an <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> pointing at the resolved URL. Same syntax as Word templates.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Loops and Tables</h3>

<p>Loop syntax is identical to Word templates. For repeating table rows, either pattern works &mdash; DocGen auto-expands to the enclosing <code>&lt;tr&gt;</code> (or <code>&lt;li&gt;</code> for lists), exactly the way it auto-expands to <code>&lt;w:tr&gt;</code> in Word.</p>

<pre style="background:#f4f6f9;padding:0.75rem;border-radius:4px;"><code>&lt;table&gt;
  &lt;thead&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;th&gt;Product&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;Amount&lt;/th&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/thead&gt;
  &lt;tbody&gt;
    &lt;!-- Pattern A: loop wraps the row --&gt;
    &#123;#OpportunityLineItems&#125;
    &lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;&#123;Product2.Name&#125;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;&#123;TotalPrice:currency&#125;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
    &#123;/OpportunityLineItems&#125;

    &lt;!-- Pattern B: loop inside the row (DocGen expands to the &lt;tr&gt;) --&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;&#123;#OpportunityLineItems&#125;&lt;td&gt;&#123;Product2.Name&#125;&lt;/td&gt;&#123;/OpportunityLineItems&#125;&lt;/tr&gt;
  &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>Bulk Generation &amp; Giant Query</h3>

<p>HTML templates work with every generation path: single-record, Bulk Generation (individual PDFs per record <em>or</em> merged into one PDF), and the Giant Query pipeline (60K+ row child relationships handled via batched rendering). Same 12 MB Queueable heap envelope, same 50,000-row batch ceiling, same Flow action.</p>

<h3>Known limitations</h3>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Barcodes / QR codes</strong> &mdash; <code>&#123;*Field:qr&#125;</code> etc. are currently Word-only. In HTML templates the tag falls back to plain text substitution. On the roadmap.</li>
    <li><strong>DOCX output</strong> &mdash; not applicable. HTML templates are PDF-only.</li>
    <li><strong>Signatures</strong> &mdash; <code>&#123;@Signature_Role&#125;</code> flows haven't been validated against HTML templates yet. Use Word templates if you need signatures today.</li>
    <li><strong>Page counters + rich header/footer content</strong> &mdash; see Page Numbers above. Flying Saucer flattens the margin box to text when counters are present.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Troubleshooting</h3>

<ul>
    <li><strong>"Your company doesn't support the following file types: .zip"</strong> &mdash; this error comes from Salesforce's org-level File Upload Security. DocGen's LWC extracts the zip client-side and never uploads the zip itself, so this shouldn't appear in normal use. If you see it, hard-refresh the page (Cmd+Shift+R / Ctrl+Shift+R) to clear any cached bundle.</li>
    <li><strong>Images show as broken squares in the PDF</strong> &mdash; <code>Blob.toPdf</code> can only fetch images via relative <code>/sfc/</code> URLs; it can't reach arbitrary HTTPS URLs (no session ID). Make sure the image source is one of: a file in the zip, a data URI in the HTML, a <code>&#123;%Image:N&#125;</code> tag, or a <code>&#123;%FieldName&#125;</code> pointing at a real ContentVersion.</li>
    <li><strong>Page numbers appearing without a configured header/footer</strong> &mdash; your template's source HTML already has <code>@page &#123; @bottom-center &#123; content: counter(page) ... &#125; &#125;</code>. Google Docs' Web Page export sometimes includes this automatically. Either remove the <code>@page</code> block from the HTML body before upload, or accept it (many users actually want page numbers).</li>
    <li><strong>Bulk merge PDF is blank or cut off</strong> &mdash; fixed in v1.62.0. v1.61.0 had a bug concatenating multiple full-HTML snippets that caused Flying Saucer to abandon rendering after the first few records. Upgrade the package.</li>
    <li><strong>Merge tag shows up literally in the PDF (e.g. the text "&#123;Name&#125;")</strong> &mdash; the tag didn't resolve. Check that the field name is correct and in your Query Config, and that the WYSIWYG editor didn't HTML-encode the braces (DocGen decodes <code>&amp;#123;</code> and <code>&amp;#125;</code> automatically, but very non-standard editors could still trip this).</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="versioning">Template Versioning</h2>

<p>Every time you upload a new file, a new version is created. You can view version history, download any version, and restore a previous version at any time. The most recent upload is always the active version.</p>

<h2 id="import-export">Import &amp; Export Templates</h2>

<p>Move templates between orgs using the portable <code>.docgen.json</code> format:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Export:</strong> Click the row action menu on any template &gt; Export. Downloads a JSON file with all metadata, query config, and the template file.</li>
    <li><strong>Import:</strong> Click Import Template in the Command Hub, upload the JSON file. The template is recreated with all settings intact.</li>
</ul>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Tip:</strong> This is the easiest way to move templates from sandbox to production, or to share templates with other orgs.
</div>

<!-- ==================== MERGE TAGS ==================== -->

<h2 id="field-tags">Field Tags</h2>

<p>Place tags in your Word, Excel, or PowerPoint template. DocGen replaces them with live Salesforce data at generation time. Here's a complete reference of every tag type:</p>

<h3>Basic Field Tags</h3>
<p>Wrap any Salesforce field API name in curly braces. The tag is replaced with the field's value from the record.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type in Template</th><th>What Appears in Output</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Name}</code></td><td>Acme Corporation</td><td>Standard field</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Email}</code></td><td>john@acme.com</td><td>Any standard field</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Phone}</code></td><td>(317) 555-0100</td><td>Phone fields</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Custom_Field__c}</code></td><td>Gold Tier</td><td>Custom fields use API name</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{CreatedDate}</code></td><td>2026-03-18T14:30:00.000Z</td><td>Raw date (add format — see below)</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Tip:</strong> The tag inherits whatever font, size, color, and style you apply to it in your Word template. If you make <code>{Name}</code> bold and 14pt in your file, the output value will be bold and 14pt.
</div>

<h2 id="parent-lookups">Parent Lookups</h2>

<p>Pull data from related records using dot notation. Add these fields in your query on step 2 (e.g., <code>Account.Name, Owner.Email</code>).</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>What It Fetches</th><th>Example Output</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Account.Name}</code></td><td>Parent Account name</td><td>Acme Corporation</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Owner.Email}</code></td><td>Record owner's email</td><td>dave@company.com</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Account.Owner.Name}</code></td><td>Account's owner (2 levels up)</td><td>Dave Moudy</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{CreatedBy.Name}</code></td><td>Who created the record</td><td>Admin User</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Account.BillingCity}</code></td><td>Parent's billing city</td><td>Indianapolis</td></tr>
</table>

<p>You can go multiple levels deep — just make sure each level is in your query: <code>Account.Name, Account.Owner.Name, Account.Owner.Email</code></p>

<h2 id="child-loops">Child Record Loops</h2>

<p>Repeat a section of your document for each child record. Use <code>{#RelationshipName}</code> to start the loop and <code>{/RelationshipName}</code> to end it. The relationship name matches your SOQL subquery.</p>

<h3>Example: Loop in a paragraph</h3>
<p>If your Account has 3 Contacts, here's what happens:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type in Template</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#Contacts}</code><br/>Name: <code>{FirstName}</code> <code>{LastName}</code> — <code>{Title}</code><br/><code>{/Contacts}</code></td></tr>
</table>

<table>
    <tr><th>What Appears in Output (3 Contacts)</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Name: John Smith — VP Sales<br/>Name: Sarah Johnson — CEO<br/>Name: Mike Chen — CTO</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Everything between <code>{#Contacts}</code> and <code>{/Contacts}</code> repeats once per child record. This works with paragraphs, bullet points, table rows — any content block.</p>

<h2 id="repeating-tables">Repeating Table Rows</h2>

<p>The most common use of child loops. Put <code>{#ChildName}</code> in the first cell and <code>{/ChildName}</code> in the last cell of the <strong>same data row</strong>. The header row stays fixed.</p>

<h3>What you type in your Word template:</h3>
<table>
    <tr><th>Product</th><th>Quantity</th><th>Unit Price</th><th>Total</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#OpportunityLineItems}{Name}</code></td><td><code>{Quantity}</code></td><td><code>{UnitPrice:currency}</code></td><td><code>{TotalPrice:currency}{/OpportunityLineItems}</code></td></tr>
</table>

<h3>What appears in the generated document:</h3>
<table>
    <tr><th>Product</th><th>Quantity</th><th>Unit Price</th><th>Total</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Enterprise License</td><td>10</td><td>$5,000.00</td><td>$50,000.00</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Implementation Services</td><td>1</td><td>$15,000.00</td><td>$15,000.00</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Annual Support</td><td>10</td><td>$1,000.00</td><td>$10,000.00</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Key rule:</strong> The opening tag <code>{#...}</code> goes in the <strong>first cell</strong> and the closing tag <code>{/...}</code> goes in the <strong>last cell</strong> of the same row. The header row is never touched. All table formatting (borders, shading, column widths) carries through to every generated row.
</div>

<h3>Another example — Contact list:</h3>
<table>
    <tr><th>Name</th><th>Title</th><th>Email</th><th>Phone</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#Contacts}{FirstName} {LastName}</code></td><td><code>{Title}</code></td><td><code>{Email}</code></td><td><code>{Phone}{/Contacts}</code></td></tr>
</table>
<p>Becomes:</p>
<table>
    <tr><th>Name</th><th>Title</th><th>Email</th><th>Phone</th></tr>
    <tr><td>John Smith</td><td>VP Sales</td><td>john@acme.com</td><td>(317) 555-0100</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Sarah Johnson</td><td>CEO</td><td>sarah@acme.com</td><td>(317) 555-0200</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="conditionals">Conditional Sections</h2>

<p>Show or hide content based on a field value. Same syntax as loops, but with a boolean or text field instead of a child relationship.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>When It Shows</th><th>When It's Hidden</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#IsActive}Active customer{/IsActive}</code></td><td>Field is <strong>true</strong></td><td>Field is <strong>false</strong></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#Description}See notes: {Description}{/Description}</code></td><td>Field has a value</td><td>Field is blank/null</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#HasDiscount}Discount applied!{/HasDiscount}</code></td><td>Checkbox is checked</td><td>Checkbox is unchecked</td></tr>
</table>

<p>The entire block — including any text, tables, or images between the tags — is removed from the output when the condition is false or blank. This works for paragraphs, table rows, and multi-line content.</p>

<h3>Else Blocks</h3>

<p>Use <code>{:else}</code> inside a conditional to show alternative content when the condition is false:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>Output (true)</th><th>Output (false/blank)</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#IsActive}Active{:else}Inactive{/IsActive}</code></td><td>Active</td><td>Inactive</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#Industry}Sector: {Industry}{:else}No industry on file{/Industry}</code></td><td>Sector: Technology</td><td>No industry on file</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Inverse Conditionals</h3>

<p>Use the <code>{^Field}</code> prefix (caret instead of hash) to show content only when a field is <strong>false, blank, or null</strong> — the opposite of <code>{#Field}</code>:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>When It Shows</th><th>When It's Hidden</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{^HasDiscount}No discount applied{/HasDiscount}</code></td><td>Field is <strong>false</strong> or blank</td><td>Field is <strong>true</strong> or has a value</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{^Email}No email on file{/Email}</code></td><td>Email is <strong>blank/null</strong></td><td>Email has a value</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Inverse conditionals also support <code>{:else}</code> blocks:</p>
<p><code>{^HasDiscount}Standard pricing{:else}Discount applied{/HasDiscount}</code></p>

<h2 id="comparisons">Comparisons (IF / ELSE)</h2>

<p>Compare a field against a specific value using <code>{#IF Field operator Value}</code>. Supports both string and numeric comparisons.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>Output</th><th>Operator</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#IF Industry = Technology}Tech partner{/IF}</code></td><td>Tech partner (when Industry is "Technology")</td><td>Equals</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#IF Amount > 50000}Premium{:else}Standard{/IF}</code></td><td>Premium (when Amount &gt; 50000)</td><td>Greater than</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#IF Status != Closed}Still open{/IF}</code></td><td>Still open (when Status is not "Closed")</td><td>Not equals</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#IF Quantity >= 100}Bulk order{/IF}</code></td><td>Bulk order (when Quantity &ge; 100)</td><td>Greater or equal</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="tip"><strong>Supported operators:</strong> <code>=</code> <code>!=</code> <code>&gt;</code> <code>&lt;</code> <code>&gt;=</code> <code>&lt;=</code> — Numeric comparison is attempted first; falls back to alphabetical string comparison.</div>

<h2 id="formatting">Date &amp; Number Formatting</h2>

<p>Add a format specifier after a colon to control how values display:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>What Appears</th><th>Format Type</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{CloseDate:MM/dd/yyyy}</code></td><td>03/18/2026</td><td>US date</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{CloseDate:dd/MM/yyyy}</code></td><td>18/03/2026</td><td>International date</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{CreatedDate:MMMM d, yyyy}</code></td><td>March 18, 2026</td><td>Long date</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Amount:currency}</code></td><td>$500,000.00</td><td>Currency</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Rate:percent}</code></td><td>15.5%</td><td>Percentage</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Quantity:number}</code></td><td>1,234</td><td>Number with commas</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Price:#,##0.00}</code></td><td>1,234.56</td><td>Custom decimal format</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{IsActive:checkbox}</code></td><td>[X] or [ ]</td><td>Checkbox (true/false)</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="tip"><strong>Checkbox format</strong> renders <code>[X]</code> for truthy values and <code>[ ]</code> for false/blank. Use it inline with labels: <code>Active: {IsActive:checkbox}  Discount: {HasDiscount:checkbox}</code></div>

<h3>International Currency &amp; Locale Formatting</h3>

<p>For global documents, add an ISO currency code and/or locale after the format keyword. This lets you control currency symbols, number separators, and date layouts per-tag:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>What Appears</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td colspan="3"><strong>Currency with ISO Code</strong></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Amount:currency:EUR&#125;</code></td><td>&euro;1,234.56</td><td>Euro symbol, your locale's separators</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Amount:currency:GBP&#125;</code></td><td>&pound;1,234.56</td><td>British Pound</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Amount:currency:JPY&#125;</code></td><td>&yen;1,235</td><td>Japanese Yen (no decimals)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Amount:currency:INR&#125;</code></td><td>&#8377;1,234.56</td><td>Indian Rupee</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Amount:currency:CHF&#125;</code></td><td>CHF 1,234.56</td><td>Swiss Franc</td></tr>
    <tr><td colspan="3"><strong>Currency with ISO Code + Locale</strong></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Amount:currency:EUR:de_DE&#125;</code></td><td>1.234,56 &euro;</td><td>German style: dot thousands, comma decimal, symbol after</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Amount:currency:GBP:en_GB&#125;</code></td><td>&pound;1,234.56</td><td>British English formatting</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Amount:currency:BRL:pt_BR&#125;</code></td><td>1.234,56 R$</td><td>Brazilian Real in Portuguese format</td></tr>
    <tr><td colspan="3"><strong>Numbers with Locale</strong></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Quantity:number:de_DE&#125;</code></td><td>1.234.567</td><td>German: dots as thousands separators</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Quantity:number:fr_FR&#125;</code></td><td>1.234.567</td><td>French: dots as thousands separators</td></tr>
    <tr><td colspan="3"><strong>Percentages with Locale</strong></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Rate:percent:de_DE&#125;</code></td><td>15,5%</td><td>German: comma as decimal separator</td></tr>
    <tr><td colspan="3"><strong>Dates with Locale</strong></td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;CloseDate:date&#125;</code></td><td><em>(your locale's default)</em></td><td>Auto-detects from running user's locale</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;CloseDate:date:de_DE&#125;</code></td><td>18.03.2026</td><td>German date format (dd.MM.yyyy)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;CloseDate:date:ja_JP&#125;</code></td><td>2026/03/18</td><td>Japanese date format (yyyy/MM/dd)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;CloseDate:date:en_GB&#125;</code></td><td>18/03/2026</td><td>British date format (dd/MM/yyyy)</td></tr>
</table>

<p><strong>Supported currencies:</strong> USD, EUR, GBP, JPY, CNY, CHF, CAD, AUD, INR, KRW, BRL, MXN, SEK, NOK, DKK, PLN, CZK, HUF, TRY, ZAR, SGD, HKD, NZD, THB, MYR, PHP, IDR, TWD, ILS, RUB, NGN, KES, AED, SAR, COP, CLP, PEN, ARS, EGP, GHS.</p>

<p><strong>Supported locales:</strong> en_US, en_GB, en_AU, de_DE, de_CH, fr_FR, fr_CH, es_ES, it_IT, pt_BR, nl_NL, da_DK, sv_SE, nb_NO, ja_JP, zh_CN, ko_KR, ru_RU, pl_PL, cs_CZ, hu_HU, tr_TR, ro_RO, el_GR, uk_UA, id_ID, vi_VN, and more. When no locale is specified, the running user's Salesforce locale is used for the <code>:date</code> keyword.</p>

<p><strong>How it works:</strong> The base tag (<code>:currency</code>, <code>:number</code>, <code>:percent</code>) without any locale uses US-style formatting for backward compatibility. Add an ISO currency code to change the symbol. Add a locale code to change the number separators and symbol placement. The <code>:date</code> keyword uses the running user's locale by default, or an explicit locale if provided.</p>

<h3>Built-in Date &amp; Time Tags</h3>

<p>Two special merge tags resolve to the current date or time without needing a formula field. They accept the same format suffixes as any date field, so locale and custom patterns all work:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>What Appears</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Today&#125;</code></td><td>2026-04-20</td><td>Current date in default ISO format</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Today:MM/dd/yyyy&#125;</code></td><td>04/20/2026</td><td>Current date, custom pattern</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Today:MMMM d, yyyy&#125;</code></td><td>April 20, 2026</td><td>Long date pattern</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Today:date&#125;</code></td><td><em>(running user's locale default)</em></td><td>Auto-detects user's Salesforce locale</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Today:date:de_DE&#125;</code></td><td>20.04.2026</td><td>Explicit locale override</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Now&#125;</code></td><td>2026-04-20 14:30:00</td><td>Current date + time</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Now:yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm&#125;</code></td><td>2026-04-20 14:30</td><td>Custom datetime pattern</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>&#123;Now:date:ja_JP&#125;</code></td><td>2026/04/20</td><td>Now formatted as a Japanese-locale date</td></tr>
</table>

<p><strong>When to use:</strong> Stamp a "Generated on" line in a footer, time-stamp an invoice, add the current date to a contract header. Works in sync and giant-query PDFs, bulk generation, and e-signature stamped documents.</p>

<h2 id="aggregates">Aggregates (SUM, COUNT, AVG)</h2>

<p>Compute totals from child record lists. Place these <strong>outside</strong> the loop — typically below a table of line items.</p>

<h3>Example — Invoice total below a line items table:</h3>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>What Appears</th><th>How It Works</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{SUM:OpportunityLineItems.TotalPrice:currency}</code></td><td>$75,000.00</td><td>Adds up TotalPrice from all line items</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{COUNT:Contacts}</code></td><td>3</td><td>Number of child Contacts</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{AVG:OpportunityLineItems.UnitPrice:currency}</code></td><td>$7,000.00</td><td>Average unit price across line items</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{MIN:OpportunityLineItems.Quantity}</code></td><td>1</td><td>Smallest quantity</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{MAX:OpportunityLineItems.Quantity}</code></td><td>10</td><td>Largest quantity</td></tr>
</table>

<p>The pattern is <code>{FUNCTION:RelationshipName.FieldName}</code>. Add <code>:currency</code> or <code>:number</code> at the end for formatting.</p>

<div class="tip"><strong>Zero extra SOQL</strong> — aggregates are computed from child data already in memory. No additional queries needed.</div>

<h3>Full invoice example putting it all together:</h3>

<table>
    <tr><th>Product</th><th>Qty</th><th>Price</th><th>Total</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{#OpportunityLineItems}{Name}</code></td><td><code>{Quantity}</code></td><td><code>{UnitPrice:currency}</code></td><td><code>{TotalPrice:currency}{/OpportunityLineItems}</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td colspan="3" style="text-align: right;"><strong>Grand Total:</strong></td><td><code>{SUM:OpportunityLineItems.TotalPrice:currency}</code></td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="images">Dynamic Images</h2>

<p>Insert images from Salesforce Files into your document. Store a ContentVersion ID (starts with <code>068</code>) in a text field on the record, then reference it with the <code>%</code> prefix:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>What Happens</th><th>Use Case</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c}</code></td><td>Image at original size</td><td>General use</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c:200x60}</code></td><td>Fixed at 200px wide, 60px tall</td><td>Letterhead logo</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c:100%x}</code></td><td>Full page width, auto height</td><td>Banner image</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c:m100%x}</code></td><td>Shrink to fit page, never upscale</td><td>Variable-size images</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Logo__c:m100%xm50%}</code></td><td>Max width + max height</td><td>Constrained area</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{%Photo__c:150x150}</code></td><td>Square thumbnail</td><td>Contact photo</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Dynamic images work in both PDF and DOCX output. You can also embed static images directly in your Word template (company logos, watermarks, etc.) — they render in PDFs automatically without any tags.</p>

<h2 id="barcodes-qr">Barcodes &amp; QR Codes</h2>

<p>Render scannable codes from any field value. <strong>PDF output only</strong> — no external services required.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>What Appears</th><th>Use Case</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{*ProductCode}</code></td><td>Code 128 barcode (default size)</td><td>Product labels</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{*SKU:code128:300x80}</code></td><td>Barcode at 300px x 80px</td><td>Shipping labels</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{*Website:qr}</code></td><td>QR code at 150px square</td><td>Link to website</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{*TrackingUrl:qr:200}</code></td><td>QR code at 200px square</td><td>Package tracking</td></tr>
</table>

<p>QR codes support up to 255 characters. Both types render as pure CSS — generated entirely in Apex, no external services needed.</p>

<h2 id="rich-text">Rich Text Fields</h2>

<p>Rich Text Area fields automatically preserve formatting. Just use a standard tag — no special syntax:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type</th><th>What Appears</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{Description}</code></td><td>The field content with <strong>bold</strong>, <em>italic</em>, bulleted lists, numbered lists, images, hyperlinks, and tables — all preserved.</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Works in both PDF and DOCX output. Images inside rich text fields render in PDFs. PowerPoint strips rich text to plain text.</p>

<h2 id="page-breaks">Page Breaks in Loops</h2>

<p>Generate one page per child record by inserting a Word page break inside the loop:</p>

<div class="code-block">
<span class="tag">{#Opportunities}</span>
  Customer:  <span class="tag">{Account.Name}</span>
  Amount:    <span class="tag">{Amount:currency}</span>
  Close:     <span class="tag">{CloseDate:MM/dd/yyyy}</span>
               <span class="comment">&lt;-- Insert page break here (Insert &gt; Page Break in Word)</span>
<span class="tag">{/Opportunities}</span>
</div>

<p>Each Opportunity gets its own full page. Works with any child loop — invoices, receipts, certificates, packing slips.</p>

<!-- ==================== PDF FEATURES ==================== -->

<h2 id="cover-pages">Cover Pages &amp; Section Breaks</h2>

<p>Create professional documents with clean title pages and proper page structure:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Title pages</strong> — Enable "Different First Page" in your Word template (Layout &gt; Different First Page). DocGen suppresses headers and footers on page 1 so your cover page stays clean.</li>
    <li><strong>Section breaks</strong> — Section breaks in your Word template create proper page breaks in the PDF. Use Insert &gt; Page Break or Insert &gt; Section Break in Word.</li>
</ul>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Tip:</strong> Cover page detection uses the <code>&lt;w:titlePg/&gt;</code> flag in your document's section properties. No extra configuration needed — just enable it in Word.
</div>

<h2 id="headers-footers">Headers &amp; Footers in PDFs</h2>

<p>Headers and footers from your Word template carry into PDF output. They repeat on <strong>every page</strong> of the generated PDF.</p>

<ul>
    <li>Full formatting supported — bold, italic, colors, borders, font sizes</li>
    <li>Merge tags work in headers and footers (<code>{Name}</code>, <code>{Account.Name}</code>)</li>
    <li>Images work in headers and footers (company logos, etc.)</li>
    <li>Add them in Word: Insert &gt; Header or Footer</li>
    <li>Use "Different First Page" to suppress headers on a cover page</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="page-numbers">Dynamic Page Numbers</h2>

<p>Add "Page X of Y" numbering to your PDF headers or footers:</p>

<ol class="steps">
    <li>In Word, double-click the header or footer to edit it.</li>
    <li>Go to <strong>Insert &gt; Page Number</strong> and pick a position.</li>
    <li>To add "of Y", go to <strong>Insert &gt; Quick Parts &gt; Field</strong> and select <code>NumPages</code>.</li>
    <li>Format the text around it: <code>Page [PAGE] of [NUMPAGES]</code>.</li>
    <li>Generate as PDF — the numbers increment dynamically on every page.</li>
</ol>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Tip:</strong> DocGen detects Word's PAGE and NUMPAGES field codes and converts them to dynamic CSS counters. Page numbers honor the font size, color, bold, and other formatting from your Word template.
</div>

<h2 id="pdf-vs-docx">PDF vs DOCX — What Works Where</h2>

<p>Most features work in both output formats. Here are the differences:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Feature</th><th>PDF</th><th>DOCX</th></tr>
    <tr><td>All merge tags and formatting</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Bold, italic, underline, colors, font sizes</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Tables with borders, shading, column widths</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Template-embedded images</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Dynamic images from record fields</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Rich text field formatting</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Rich text images</td><td>Yes</td><td>No — use <code>{%Field}</code> image tags</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Barcodes and QR codes</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Page numbers in headers/footers</td><td>Yes</td><td>N/A (Word handles natively)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Cover page (no header on page 1)</td><td>Yes</td><td>N/A (Word handles natively)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Custom fonts (Calibri, branded, etc.)</td><td>No — falls back to Helvetica</td><td>Yes — preserves original fonts</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Clickable hyperlinks</td><td>No — rendered as styled text</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> If you need barcodes, QR codes, or dynamic page numbers — generate as PDF. If you need custom fonts or clickable hyperlinks — generate as DOCX.
</div>

<h2 id="pdf-fonts">PDF Fonts</h2>

<p>Salesforce's PDF engine supports these built-in fonts:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Font</th><th>CSS Name</th><th>When It's Used</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Helvetica</td><td><code>sans-serif</code></td><td>Default for all text</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Times</td><td><code>serif</code></td><td>If explicitly set in template</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Courier</td><td><code>monospace</code></td><td>Fixed-width text</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Arial Unicode MS</td><td>(automatic)</td><td>Chinese, Japanese, Korean, Thai, Arabic, Hebrew</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Custom fonts from your Word template (Calibri, Cambria, branded typefaces) <strong>fall back to Helvetica</strong> in PDF output. If custom fonts matter, generate as DOCX — Word preserves the original fonts.</p>

<h2 id="pdf-limitations">PDF Limitations</h2>

<p>These are Salesforce platform limitations, not DocGen bugs:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Not Supported in PDF</th><th>Workaround</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Custom fonts (<code>@font-face</code>)</td><td>Generate as DOCX</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Text boxes and shapes</td><td>Use tables for layout</td></tr>
    <tr><td>SmartArt and charts</td><td>Insert as images in your template</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Clickable hyperlinks</td><td>Links work in DOCX output</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CSS Grid / Flexbox</td><td>Use tables (CSS 2.1 only)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Even/odd page headers</td><td>Same header on all pages</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Multiple section-specific headers</td><td>One header/footer set per document</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Multi-column layouts</td><td>Use tables for column layouts</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="rtl">RTL Languages (Hebrew / Arabic)</h2>

<p>DocGen supports right-to-left text in PDF output:</p>

<ul>
    <li>Hebrew and Arabic characters render correctly using Arial Unicode MS</li>
    <li>Paragraphs with <code>&lt;w:bidi/&gt;</code> align right automatically</li>
    <li>Tables with RTL layout reverse column order</li>
    <li>Mixed content (Hebrew label + English merge value) works correctly</li>
</ul>

<div class="warning">
    <strong>Known limitation:</strong> Long RTL paragraphs that wrap to multiple lines may have continuation lines starting from the left. This is a Salesforce PDF engine limitation.
</div>

<!-- ==================== DOCUMENT GENERATION ==================== -->

<h2 id="generate-single">Generate from a Record</h2>

<ol class="steps">
    <li>Navigate to any record page (Account, Opportunity, Contact, etc.).</li>
    <li>Find the <strong>Document Generator</strong> component on the page.</li>
    <li>Select a template from the dropdown (if a default is set for that object, it's pre-selected).</li>
    <li>Choose <strong>Download</strong> or <strong>Save to Record</strong>.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Generate Document</strong>.</li>
</ol>

<p>Your template selection persists if you switch between the Create Document, Document Packet, and Combine PDFs tabs.</p>

<h2 id="document-packets">Document Packets</h2>

<p>Generate multiple templates at once and merge them into a single PDF:</p>

<ol class="steps">
    <li>Switch to the <strong>Create Packet</strong> tab in the Document Generator.</li>
    <li>Select multiple templates using the dual-listbox.</li>
    <li>Optionally include existing PDFs already on the record.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Generate Packet</strong> — all documents merge into one PDF.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="pdf-merge">PDF Merge &amp; Child Record PDFs</h2>

<p>Five ways to combine PDFs:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Mode</th><th>What It Does</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Generate &amp; Merge</strong></td><td>Generate a doc, then append existing PDFs from the record</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Document Packets</strong></td><td>Generate from multiple templates, merge into one PDF</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Merge Only</strong></td><td>Combine existing PDFs on the record with drag-and-drop ordering</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Child Record PDFs</strong></td><td>Pull PDFs from child records (e.g., all Opportunity PDFs under an Account)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Bulk Merge</strong></td><td>After bulk generation, merge all generated PDFs into one download</td></tr>
</table>

<p>For <strong>Child Record PDFs</strong>: select the child relationship, optionally filter with a WHERE clause (e.g., <code>StageName = 'Closed Won'</code>), browse PDFs grouped by child record, select the ones you want, and merge.</p>

<p>All merging runs client-side in your browser — no server-side size limits on the merged output.</p>

<h2 id="bulk-generation">Bulk Generation</h2>

<p>Generate documents for hundreds of records at once from the <strong>Bulk Generation</strong> tab in the Command Hub.</p>

<ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Select a template</strong> and optionally preview with a sample record.</li>
    <li><strong>Enter a filter</strong> — a SOQL WHERE clause like <code>StageName = 'Closed Won' AND CloseDate = THIS_MONTH</code>. Click Validate to check syntax and see matching record count.</li>
    <li><strong>Configure the job</strong> — set batch size, output mode (individual files, merged packet, or both), and give it a name.</li>
    <li><strong>Submit</strong> — real-time progress tracking with auto-refresh. View results in Recent Jobs.</li>
</ol>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Saved Queries</h3>
    <p>Save frequently-used WHERE clauses with a name and description. Load them with one click when setting up future bulk jobs. Great for monthly invoices, quarterly reports, or any recurring generation task.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Bulk Merge</h3>
    <p>After a bulk job completes, click the merge icon on the job row to download all generated PDFs combined into a single file.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="giant-query">Giant Query (2,000+ Rows)</h2>

<p>DocGen automatically detects large datasets and switches to batch processing. Same template, same button — the complexity is invisible to the user.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th></th><th>Standard Engine</th><th>Giant Query Engine</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>When</strong></td><td>&lt; 2,000 child records</td><td>&gt; 2,000 child records</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Detection</strong></td><td>Automatic</td><td>Automatic</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Speed</strong></td><td>2-5 seconds</td><td>1-5 minutes (async)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Output</strong></td><td>Download or save</td><td>Saved to record automatically</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Tested up to 28,000+ rows. Ideal for transaction logs, price books, audit trails, and bulk data reports. Uses cursor-based pagination (500 rows per page) so it never hits heap limits.</p>

<div class="warning">
    <strong>Giant Query limitation:</strong> ORDER BY in child subqueries is not yet supported in Giant Query mode. Records will be returned in Salesforce's default order. If sort order matters, use the standard engine (under 2,000 rows) or sort in your template's table after generation. This is on the roadmap.
</div>

