<h2 id="apex-provider">Custom Apex Data Provider</h2>

<p>For advanced use cases, implement the <code>DocGenDataProvider</code> interface to supply custom data from external APIs, computed fields, or cross-object aggregations. Select "Apex Provider" as the query type in the template configuration and specify your class name.</p>

<!-- ==================== E-SIGNATURES ==================== -->

<h2 id="sig-overview">Electronic Signatures</h2>

<p>DocGen includes a built-in Simple Electronic Signature (SES) system. Signers receive an email, verify their identity with a 6-digit PIN, review the document, type their name, and agree to sign electronically. Every step is recorded in a tamper-evident audit trail.</p>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Legal Standard:</strong> Typed-name signatures are legally valid under the US ESIGN Act and UETA. They carry the same legal weight as drawn signatures for SES use cases. DocGen captures consent, email verification, IP address, and user agent for every signature.
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>How It Works</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Email PIN Verification</strong> &mdash; Signers enter their email and receive a 6-digit code. This proves they control the inbox at the moment of signing. PINs expire after 10 minutes and lock after 3 failed attempts.</li>
        <li><strong>Consent Capture</strong> &mdash; Every signer must check an explicit consent checkbox before signing. The consent timestamp is recorded on the audit record with field history tracking.</li>
        <li><strong>Document Hash</strong> &mdash; A SHA-256 hash of the final signed PDF is computed and stored on the audit record. This proves the document has not been modified since signing.</li>
        <li><strong>Verification Certificate</strong> &mdash; Every signed PDF includes a certificate block at the bottom showing signer names, roles, timestamps, and a verification URL. Anyone can verify the document's authenticity.</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<h2 id="sig-templates">Signature Template Setup</h2>

<p>Add signature placeholders to your Word template using the <code>{@Signature_Role}</code> syntax. The <code>@</code> prefix tells DocGen to preserve the tag during template merge and replace it with the signer's typed name after all signatures are collected.</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>What You Type in Template</th><th>What Appears After Signing</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{@Signature_Buyer}</code></td><td>Electronically signed by John Smith on 2026-04-08 10:30:00 PDT</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{@Signature_Seller}</code></td><td>Electronically signed by Jane Doe on 2026-04-08 14:15:00 PDT</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>{@Signature}</code></td><td>Used for single-signer documents (no role name needed)</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Multi-Signer:</strong> Add multiple signature placeholders for different roles. Each signer gets their own email with a unique link. The PDF is only generated after <strong>all</strong> signers have completed. Unsigned placeholders are preserved until the signer completes.
</div>

<p>Use any role name &mdash; it maps to the Signer Role picklist which includes: Buyer, Seller, Husband, Wife, Borrower, Co-Borrower, Lender, Guarantor, Witness, Notary, Agent, Attorney, Applicant, Co-Applicant, Trustee, Beneficiary, Landlord, Tenant, Partner, Signer.</p>

<h2 id="sig-flow">The Signing Flow</h2>

<p>Here is what each signer experiences when they receive a signature request:</p>

<ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Email:</strong> Signer receives a branded email with a secure link. The link expires after 48 hours.</li>
    <li><strong>Verify:</strong> Signer enters their email address, receives a 6-digit PIN via email, and enters it to prove inbox control. PINs expire after 10 minutes. After 3 failed attempts, the link is permanently locked.</li>
    <li><strong>Review:</strong> The signer expands the document preview to read the full merged document before signing. This includes all Salesforce data already merged into the template.</li>
    <li><strong>Sign:</strong> Signer types their full name, checks the consent checkbox ("I agree to sign this document electronically"), and clicks Sign Document.</li>
</ol>

<p>For multi-signer documents, non-final signers see a "Waiting for other signers" message after signing. The final signer triggers PDF generation with all signatures stamped.</p>

<div class="warning">
    <strong>Security:</strong> PINs are hashed with SHA-256 before storage &mdash; plaintext is never saved to Salesforce. Signing tokens are 64-character cryptographic hashes (SHA-256 of AES-256 random bytes + signer email). The signer's IP address is captured server-side via X-Forwarded-For headers.
</div>

<h2 id="sig-verify">Document Verification</h2>

<p>Every signed PDF includes an Electronic Signature Certificate at the bottom of the document showing:</p>

<ul>
    <li>Document ID (Signature Request record ID)</li>
    <li>Completion date and time</li>
    <li>Each signer's name, role, email, and email verification timestamp</li>
    <li>A verification URL pointing to the DocGen Verify page</li>
</ul>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Online Verification</h3>
    <p>The verify page (<code>/apex/DocGenVerify</code>) supports two verification methods:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>URL with Document ID:</strong> The certificate link includes the request ID. Opening it shows the full audit trail for all signers &mdash; names, emails, roles, timestamps, consent status, PIN verification, and the SHA-256 hash.</li>
        <li><strong>File Upload:</strong> Drag any PDF onto the verify page. The browser computes a SHA-256 hash locally (the file never leaves the browser) and checks it against the audit record. If it matches, the document is authentic.</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Field History Tracking:</strong> All key audit fields (signer name, email, signed date, hash, IP address, consent, PIN verification) have field history tracking enabled. If an admin modifies an audit record, Salesforce logs the change automatically.
</div>

<h2 id="sig-admin">Signature Admin Setup</h2>

<p>Complete these steps to enable signatures in your org:</p>

<ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Enable the Blob.toPdf() Release Update.</strong> Go to Setup &gt; Release Updates and enable <em>"Use the Visualforce PDF Rendering Service for Blob.toPdf() Invocations"</em>. This is required for both regular PDF generation and signed PDF generation.</li>
    <li><strong>Create a Salesforce Site.</strong> Go to Setup &gt; Sites &gt; create a new site. Set the active Visualforce page to <code>DocGenSignature</code>. This is the public page that external signers access &mdash; no Salesforce login required.</li>
    <li><strong>Assign Guest Permissions.</strong> Assign the <strong>DocGen Guest Signature</strong> permission set to the site's guest user profile. This grants the guest user access to the signature Apex classes and custom objects.</li>
    <li><strong>Configure Email Branding.</strong> In the DocGen Command Hub, go to the <strong>Signatures</strong> tab. Set your company name, brand color, logo URL, and customize the email subject and message template.</li>
    <li><strong>Set the Site URL.</strong> In Signature Settings, enter your site's base URL (e.g., <code>https://yourorg.my.salesforce-sites.com/signatures</code>). This ensures signing links and verification URLs resolve correctly.</li>
    <li><strong>Set Email Deliverability.</strong> Go to Setup &gt; Email &gt; Deliverability and set Access Level to <strong>All Email</strong>. PIN verification emails will not be delivered if this is set to "System Email Only".</li>
    <li><strong>Assign User Permissions.</strong> Users who create signature requests need the <strong>DocGen Admin</strong> or <strong>DocGen User</strong> permission set.</li>
</ol>

<table>
    <tr><th>Object</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>DocGen Signature Request</strong></td><td>Parent record for a signing session. Links to a template and related record. Status: Sent &rarr; Viewed &rarr; In Progress &rarr; Signed.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>DocGen Signer</strong></td><td>One per signer per request. Tracks status, typed name, PIN verification, consent. Child of Signature Request.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>DocGen Signature Audit</strong></td><td>Immutable audit record created at signing time. Stores IP, user agent, document hash, consent flag, PIN verification timestamp. Field history tracking enabled.</td></tr>
</table>

<!-- ==================== ADMIN ==================== -->

<h2 id="permissions">Permissions &amp; Sharing</h2>

<table>
    <tr><th>Permission Set</th><th>Who</th><th>Access</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>DocGen Admin</strong></td><td>Template builders, admins</td><td>Full access — create, edit, delete templates, bulk generate</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>DocGen User</strong></td><td>End users</td><td>Generate documents, use templates (no admin)</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Field-level security is enforced — users only see fields they have permission to read. Record sharing follows standard Salesforce rules. Generated files are visible to anyone with access to the record.</p>

<p>Template access uses standard Salesforce sharing — sharing rules, manual sharing, and role hierarchy. No custom sharing UI needed.</p>

<h2 id="governor-limits">Governor Limits</h2>

<p>DocGen is designed to work within Salesforce governor limits. Here's how it handles them:</p>

<table>
    <tr><th>Limit</th><th>How DocGen Handles It</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>6 MB heap (sync)</strong></td><td>DOCX uses client-side assembly; PDF uses zero-heap image pipeline</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>12 MB heap (async)</strong></td><td>Bulk generation uses batch size 1 = fresh heap per record</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>~3 MB PDF save</strong></td><td>Download has no size limit; only saving to record has this cap</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>4 MB Aura payload</strong></td><td>Download works for any size DOCX; saving has this limit</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>100 SOQL queries</strong></td><td>Multi-level queries use 1 SOQL per relationship depth</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>50,000+ child records</strong></td><td>Giant Query auto-detected, processed async with cursor pagination</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Tip:</strong> If bulk generation is slow, reduce batch size to 1. Each batch gets a fresh heap limit, so complex templates with images or many child records process reliably.
</div>

<h2 id="known-limitations">Known Limitations</h2>

<p>These are things DocGen does <strong>not</strong> support. Most are Salesforce platform constraints, not DocGen bugs. Knowing these upfront saves you from building a template that won't work as expected.</p>

<h3>PDF Output — What Doesn't Work</h3>

<table>
    <tr><th>Does NOT Work</th><th>Why</th><th>Workaround</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Custom fonts (Calibri, branded typefaces)</td><td><code>Blob.toPdf()</code> only has 4 built-in fonts</td><td>Generate as DOCX — Word preserves original fonts</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>@font-face</code> CSS</td><td>Not supported by the PDF renderer</td><td>Generate as DOCX</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Text boxes and Word shapes</td><td>Drawing objects aren't converted to HTML</td><td>Use tables for layout instead</td></tr>
    <tr><td>SmartArt and charts</td><td>Not rendered in the HTML conversion</td><td>Insert as a static image in your template</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Clickable hyperlinks</td><td>PDF renderer outputs styled text, not real links</td><td>Links work in DOCX output</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CSS Grid / Flexbox</td><td>PDF renderer only supports CSS 2.1</td><td>Use tables</td></tr>
    <tr><td>JavaScript in templates</td><td>Ignored by the renderer</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Even/odd page headers</td><td>Not currently supported</td><td>Same header on all pages</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Multiple section-specific headers</td><td>One header/footer set per document</td><td>Use page breaks, not section-specific headers</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Multi-column layouts</td><td>CSS columns not supported by the PDF engine</td><td>Use tables for column layouts</td></tr>
    <tr><td>E-signatures (QES)</td><td>SES signatures are built-in; Qualified Electronic Signatures (EU eIDAS) require a certified provider</td><td>Use built-in SES for most use cases; integrate with a QES provider for EU regulatory requirements</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>DOCX Output — What Doesn't Work</h3>

<table>
    <tr><th>Does NOT Work</th><th>Why</th><th>Workaround</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Barcodes and QR codes</td><td>These are rendered as CSS in the PDF pipeline only</td><td>Generate as PDF for barcodes/QR</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Rich text images</td><td>Images inside Rich Text Area fields don't carry into DOCX</td><td>Use <code>{%Field}</code> image tags or generate as PDF</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Dynamic page numbers</td><td>PAGE/NUMPAGES are PDF-only features</td><td>Word handles page numbers natively — add them in Word's header</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Excel &amp; PowerPoint — What Doesn't Work</h3>

<table>
    <tr><th>Does NOT Work</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td>PDF output</td><td>Excel and PowerPoint output in their native format only (.xlsx, .pptx)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Images</td><td>Dynamic images and barcodes are Word/PDF only</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Rich text formatting</td><td>Rich text fields are stripped to plain text in PowerPoint</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Headers and footers</td><td>Headers/footers are a Word/PDF feature</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>General Limitations</h3>

<table>
    <tr><th>Limitation</th><th>Details</th></tr>
    <tr><td>~3 MB PDF save limit</td><td>Saving a PDF to a record is capped at ~3 MB by Salesforce. Download has no limit. Use Download for large PDFs.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>4 MB Aura payload limit</td><td>Saving a DOCX to a record is capped at 4 MB. Download works for any size.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>RTL text wrapping</td><td>Long Hebrew/Arabic paragraphs that wrap to multiple lines may have continuation lines starting from the left. This is a Salesforce PDF engine limitation.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>No live preview before generating</td><td>You generate the document to see results. Use the sample record preview on step 2 to verify your query returns the right data.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Giant Query: no ORDER BY</td><td>ORDER BY in child subqueries is not yet supported when Giant Query mode activates (2,000+ rows). Records return in Salesforce default order. Standard engine supports ORDER BY.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>One header/footer set</td><td>PDFs support one header and one footer across the entire document. "Different First Page" is supported (cover pages), but section-specific headers are not.</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="tip">
    <strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> If something doesn't work in PDF, try DOCX. If it doesn't work in DOCX, try PDF. Between the two formats, most use cases are covered.
</div>

<h2 id="troubleshooting">Troubleshooting</h2>

<div class="card">
    <h3>PDF shows raw CSS text instead of formatted content</h3>
    <p>Enable the <strong>Blob.toPdf() Release Update</strong> in Setup &gt; Release Updates. This is the most common issue and the first thing to check.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Images appear broken in PDF</h3>
    <p>Make sure the image field contains a ContentVersion ID (starts with <code>068</code>). The file must be committed (not just uploaded) in Salesforce Files.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Fields show as blank in output</h3>
    <p>Check that the field is included in the template's query configuration (step 2) and that the running user has FLS access to the field. Open the template, go to step 2, and verify the field is in the query.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Bulk generation is slow or hitting limits</h3>
    <p>Reduce batch size to 1 for complex templates with images or many child records. Each batch gets a fresh 12 MB heap limit.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Page numbers not showing in PDF</h3>
    <p>Use Word's built-in Insert &gt; Page Number feature (not typed text). DocGen detects the PAGE and NUMPAGES field codes automatically.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Hebrew/Arabic text is blank in PDF</h3>
    <p>Ensure the Word template has RTL paragraph properties set (<code>&lt;w:bidi/&gt;</code>). DocGen auto-detects RTL and applies Arial Unicode MS font. Generate as DOCX if the PDF engine can't render specific glyphs.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Custom fonts look different in PDF</h3>
    <p>This is expected. PDF output only supports Helvetica, Times, Courier, and Arial Unicode MS. All other fonts fall back to Helvetica. Generate as DOCX if you need branded fonts.</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
    <h3>Cover page has headers/footers showing</h3>
    <p>In Word, go to Layout &gt; check "Different First Page". This tells DocGen to suppress headers and footers on page 1.</p>
</div>

